50|$|Constitutionality of <b>sex</b> <b>offender</b> {{registries}} in the United States {{have been}} challenged {{on a number}} of constitutional and other bases, generating substantial amount of case law. The Supreme Court of the United States has upheld <b>sex</b> <b>offender</b> registration laws each of the two times such laws have been examined by them. Those challenging the <b>sex</b> <b>offender</b> registration and related restriction statutes have claimed violations of ex post facto, due process, cruel and unusual punishment, equal protection and search and seizure. A study published in fall 2015 found that statistics cited in two U.S. Supreme Court decisions that are often cited in decisions upholding the constitutionality of <b>sex</b> <b>offender</b> policies are unfounded. Several challenges to some parts of state level <b>sex</b> <b>offender</b> laws have been honored after hearing at the state level.|$|R
